abstract: EFFORTS MAKING TO RAISE THE STEAMER KNICKERBOCKER.--The work of raising the steamer Knickerbocker was commenced this morning. abstract: STEAMER KNICKERROCKER AFLOAT.--Five steam pumps were set in motion yesterday afternoon, on this fine vessel, and in less than an hour-and-a-half she floated. They were kept in motion five hours, when canvas was drawn under the vessel, which nearly stopped the leak. As soon as she floated the deck settled back to nearly its original position, and the several joints made in the hog fame are now nearly closed.

abstract: ANOTHER PRESDYTERIAN SPLIT.- Splits are becoming common in the Presbyterian body. Last week the synod of Missouri, consisting of four presbyteries and fifty-seven churches, held its annual session in St. Louis, and after a long discussion on Slavery, resolved to form itself into an independent body. It refuses fellowship with the New School body. on account of its action at Cleveland last summer, and declares that it cannot go with the Richmond Convention.

abstract: A steam-boiler in HEYWARD'S India Rubber Works exploded this morning, and the fine buildings constituting the works were destroyed. abstract: KRAUTH.--In this City, on Thursday, Oct. 29, AUGUSTUS II, KRAUTH, senior proprietor of the New-York Mercury, aged 19 years. The Friends of the family, also the members of New-York Typographical Society, and the members of Enterprise Lodge, I. O. of O. F., are respectfully invited to attend the funeral of the decensed, from his late residence. No. 249 Broome st., on Sunday afternoon, at 2 o'clock. His remains will be interred at Cypress Hills Cemetery.

abstract: To the Editor of the New-York Times: I would ask it there is any systematic plan being put in operation as regards the employment of domestics? I heat of housekeepers who are diminishing the number of their servants, but not lowering the wages of the those they retain. May it not be hope I that this plan will not be pursued; but that the usual number will be retained--increased even--but at a reduction of wages.

abstract: We have received a copy of the resolutions adopted by the meeting held at Lecompton on the 20th of October, to protest against the rejection by GOV. WALKER and Secretary STANTON, of the fraudulent votes cast in Oxford, Johnson County, We publish them because they will enable the public to see upon what grounds this action of Gov. WALKER is to be resisted by the Pro-Slavery faction with whose plans and purposes it has interfered.
